04376nam a22006255i 9780814768938DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19961996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147689387 a10.18574/97808147689382doi  a(DE-B1597)547009  a(OCoLC)782878036  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6570.2.P 7aSOC0180002bisacsh04a362.761 aPryor, Doug W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnspeakable Acts :bWhy Men Sexually Abuse Children /cDoug W. Pryor. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tONE. Studying Offenders and Their Behavior -- tTWO. Blurring of Boundaries in Childhood -- tTHREE. Escalating Problems in Adulthood -- tFOUR. Shifting into an Offending Mode -- tFIVE. Approaching and Engaging the Victim -- tSIX. Snowballing from One Act to Many -- tSEVEN. Continuing with Regular Offending -- tEIGHT. Exiting Offending and Public Exposure -- tNINE. Answering the Question Why -- tTable 1. Recent Studies Measuring Sexual Abuse -- tAppendix A. Topical Interview Guide -- tAppendix B. Research Consent Forms -- tAppendix C. Statistical Data on Cases -- tAppendix D. The Retrospective Interpretation Problem -- tNotes -- tSuggested Reading -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sexual abuse of children is one of the most morally unsettling and emotionally inflammatory issues in American society today. It has been estimated that roughly one out of every four girls and one in ten boys experience some form of unwanted sexual attention either inside or outside the family before they reach adulthood. How should society deal with the sexual victimization of children? Should known offenders be released back into our communities? If so, where, and with what rights, should they be allowed to live? In Unspeakable Acts, Douglas W. Pryor argues that much of this debate, designed to deal with abusers after they have offended, ignores the important issue of why men cross these forbidden sexual boundaries to molest children in the first place and how the behavior can possibly be prevented before it starts. Incorporating in-depth interviews with more than thirty convicted child molesters, Pryor explores how men become involved with breaking sexual boundaries with children. He looks at how their lives prior to offending contributed to and led up to what they did, the ways that initial interest in sex with children began, the tactics offenders employed to molest their victims over time, how they felt about and reacted to their behavior between offending episodes, and how they were ultimately able to stop. The author expands our understanding of this often reviled, little understood group, leaving us with the uneasy conclusion that the moral wall separating us from what is defined as extreme, sick behavior is not as opaque as we would like to believe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aChild molesterszUnited StatesvInterviews. 0aChild sexual abusezUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Men's Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768938423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768938.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK